# Handled Home — PRD (Sprint 3D): Switch Kit + Ops Cockpit v1
**Sprint:** 3D  
**Depends on:** 3A Levels + 3B Coverage Map & Signals + 3C Growth Surfaces/Add Drawer/Home restructure  
**Product:** Handled Home (mobile-only iOS/Android)  
**Core thesis alignment:** Convert “already-handled” households by making switching **safe and frictionless**, while giving Ops a **control tower** to protect reliability, margins, and quality at launch.

---

## 0) Executive Summary (What 3D really does)
Sprint 3D operationalizes two critical scale levers:

1) **Switch Kit**: A premium, low-risk way for customers to replace incumbent providers (pool/lawn/cleaning/etc.) without confrontation, surprise pricing, or schedule chaos.  
2) **Ops Cockpit v1**: A single page that shows whether the business is healthy in a zone (capacity, proof, issues, attach rate) and what to do next.

If 3C is how you expand within households, 3D is how you **steal households** that already have vendors and run launch markets without entropy.

---

## 1) Goals

### 1.1 Customer goals (Switch)
- Switching feels safe, reversible, and non-awkward.
- I can set a **future start date** (default next cycle).
- I understand what changes (schedule, scope, proof).
- I can “trial” Handled Home without burning bridges.

### 1.2 Business goals
- Increase conversion of “I already have someone” households.
- Reduce churn risk by preventing messy handoffs.
- Increase ARR by capturing high-value incumbent categories (pool/lawn/cleaning).

### 1.3 Operational goals (Cockpit)
- Prevent overselling: zone capacity is visible and enforceable.
- Detect quality problems early via proof compliance + issue rates.
- Detect pricing/level mismatch via recommendation/courtesy upgrade patterns.
- Provide a single “what do we do next” view for launch execution.

---

## 2) Non-goals (v1 of 3D)
- Full provider marketplace recruiting flows (covered elsewhere)
- Automated cancellation messaging to old providers (can be v1.5)
- Advanced forecasting and predictive capacity (keep cockpit simple)
- Complex multi-provider “choose your provider” consumer feature (stay curated)

---

## 3) Part A — Switch Kit (Customer-Facing)

## 3.1 When Switch Kit appears (targeting rules)
Switch Kit should only surface when it’s appropriate. Sources:
- Coverage Map = PROVIDER for that category
- Switch intent = OPEN_NOW or OPEN_LATER
- Service category is eligible in customer’s zone

Entry points:
- Add Service Drawer: “Switch a service”
- Coverage Map edit screen: “Switch this to Handled Home”
- SKU detail page for incumbent-heavy categories (pool/lawn/cleaning)
- Home: subtle card only if customer has OPEN_NOW candidates

**Never show Switch Kit** for categories marked NA.

---

## 3.2 Switch Kit UX (flow)
**Design principle:** A Switch is a planned transition, not an on-demand replacement.

### Step 1 — Confirm intent (light)
Screen: “Switch [Service] to Handled Home”
- Microcopy: “We’ll start on a date you choose. No awkward conversations.”
- Choice:
  - Start next cycle (default)
  - Choose a date

### Step 2 — Collect minimum setup inputs (fast)
Only ask what is needed for execution + quality:
- Access notes (toggle + short text)
- 1 photo upload if relevant (pool equipment, gate, special area)
- For some SKUs, 1–3 sizing questions (reuse your Levels question framework)

### Step 3 — Choose transition style
Options:
- **Soft transition (recommended)**: “Keep my current provider until Handled Home starts”
- Optional (v1.5): “I want Handled Home to handle the cancellation message”

### Step 4 — Confirm plan
Confirmation page:
- “Start date: ____”
- “Your first Handled visit will be on: ____ (estimate)”
- “What to expect” bullets:
  - Proof receipts
  - Scope + level standardized
  - Adjustments happen next cycle

CTA: **Confirm Switch**

### After confirmation
- Show as a scheduled “Switch Pending” item (not an active routine service yet)
- Home screen shows a calm status: “Switch scheduled for next cycle”

---

## 3.3 Switch States + Behavior
Each Switch Request has a lifecycle:

- **DRAFT** (started, not confirmed)
- **PENDING_START** (confirmed, future start date)
- **READY_TO_SCHEDULE** (within scheduling horizon)
- **ACTIVE** (now part of routine)
- **PAUSED** (customer postponed)
- **CANCELLED** (customer cancelled before start)
- **FAILED** (ops cancelled due to capacity/coverage constraints)

Rules:
- Default activation is **next cycle**.
- If capacity or zone coverage changes, Switch may be delayed:
  - Customer gets a premium message explaining timing.

---

## 3.4 Switching + Levels (critical integration)
When switching an incumbent service, Levels must be explicit to prevent confusion:
- “We recommend Level 2 for your home” with reason
- Customer can choose Level 1/2/3
- Any provider “recommendations” post-first visit update default next cycle (3A loop)

Optional “trial” mechanic (powerful):
- For first visit only, allow “Trial at recommended level” with a clear future adjustment:
  - “We’ll ensure Handled standards on the first visit. If a higher level is required, we’ll recommend it for next cycle.”

Do **not** use surprise pricing. Always next-cycle changes.

---

## 3.5 Switching Guardrails (protect brand + ops)
- If customer tries to switch into a zone/category that is WAITLIST/CLOSED:
  - Allow a “Join switch waitlist” flow with ETA messaging
- If customer requests same-week start:
  - Only allow if capacity exists and ops rules permit
  - Otherwise default to next cycle

---

## 3.6 Switch Kit Messaging (premium tone)
Copy should emphasize calm, safety, control:
- “No awkward conversations.”
- “Start on your schedule.”
- “We’ll keep your service consistent.”
- “Proof receipts every visit.”

Avoid:
- competitor bashing
- price war messaging
- “cancel your old provider now” pressure

